---
import type { Tool } from '../data/tools';
import { type Locale } from '../data/locales';
import { toolName } from '../data/translations';

type Props = {
  tool: Tool;
  locale: Locale;
};

const { tool, locale } = Astro.props;
const useCases = tool.useCases.join(', ');
const controls = tool.controls.join(', ');
const name = toolName(locale, tool);
---

<article class="site-shell rich-article max-w-3xl py-16">
  <h2>How to use {name} well.</h2>
  <p>
    {name} is designed for people who need a fast, dependable fullscreen utility instead of a noisy page wrapped around a tiny demo.
    The goal is {tool.intent}. That matters because screen tools are usually opened in the middle of another workflow: checking a new
    monitor, lighting a quick shot, preparing a classroom display, testing color output, staging a video scene, or creating a calm ambient
    background on a spare device.
  </p>
  <p>
    The page starts with the screen itself, then keeps the controls close enough to be useful without making them the product. Open fullscreen
    mode when you want the most accurate view. Browser tabs, bookmark bars, and desktop UI can hide edge defects, change perceived contrast,
    or make a color feel less even than it really is. Fullscreen mode gives the entire panel to the utility, and the Escape hint keeps the
    interaction understandable for keyboard and assistive-technology users.
  </p>
  <p>
    Common use cases for {name.toLowerCase()} include {useCases}. Each use case benefits from a clean page because surrounding graphics
    influence perception. A white border can make grey look darker. A colorful header can change how saturated a solid color appears. A heavy
    animation can distract from pixel-level inspection. This page keeps the interface quiet and lets the screen state take priority.
  </p>
  <h2>Controls and workflow.</h2>
  <p>
    The reusable screen component includes {controls}. These controls are intentionally consistent across the site, so a person who learns one
    screen can move through color screens, testing tools, ambient screens, fake screens, and prank screens without relearning the interface.
    Designers can copy values, testers can adjust brightness, creators can enter an exact color, and casual users can simply press Fullscreen.
  </p>
  <p>
    Brightness should be changed gradually. Displays do not all respond the same way, and a phone, OLED television, office monitor, and projector
    can produce very different perceived output at the same nominal brightness. If you are checking for panel defects, raise brightness enough
    to reveal the issue, then lower it again to a comfortable level. If you are using the screen as light, test the scene through the camera or
    the viewer that matters rather than relying on how the panel looks from your chair.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keyboard shortcuts make repeat use faster. Press F for fullscreen, R for a random color where available, and C to copy the current color.
    The controls are standard form controls wherever possible, which keeps the page accessible and predictable. The page also respects reduced
    motion preferences for motion-heavy effects, because a screen saver or prank page should not become uncomfortable for users who prefer a
    calmer interface.
  </p>
  <h2>Display testing notes.</h2>
  <p>
    If you are using {name.toLowerCase()} to inspect a device, clean the glass first and check in stable lighting. Dust, fingerprints,
    reflections, and screen protectors can look like panel defects. View the screen straight on, then from shallow angles. Some issues only show
    in one position. For pixel checks, compare multiple solid colors. A pixel that disappears on black but appears on red may be a stuck subpixel
    rather than a completely dead pixel.
  </p>
  <p>
    Browser tools are useful for discovery and documentation, but they are not lab instruments. A color value shown by the page is exact in the
    code, while the emitted light depends on the display, brightness curve, panel technology, operating-system color management, browser behavior,
    and ambient light. For professional color-critical work, pair this utility with calibrated hardware and a color-managed workflow.
  </p>
  <h2>Why this page is built differently.</h2>
  <p>
    Many screen utility sites treat every page as a keyword container. Free Online Screen is structured as a product: consistent navigation,
    clear categories, related tools, accessible controls, schema, canonical URLs, hreflang support, and static rendering. The result is faster for
    users and easier for search engines to understand. It also means the page can grow into offline mode, recent colors, favorites, wallpaper
    downloads, timers, and ambient modes without turning into a pile of unrelated widgets.
  </p>
  <p>
    For best results, bookmark the exact page you use most often. Color pages are useful for quick lighting and display checks. Testing pages
    are better when you need a repeatable inspection sequence. Ambient pages are designed for long-running, low-distraction use. Fake and prank
    pages are browser visuals only; they should be used responsibly and never to deceive someone in a harmful context.
  </p>
  <p>
    {name} is free, accountless, and static-first. That keeps load time low, avoids unnecessary tracking, and makes the tool feel immediate.
    The screen should be available when the user needs it, not after a heavy bundle, a modal, or a signup prompt.
  </p>
</article>
